Commentary.Commentary: The second innings is set to begin! The Sri Lanka players stride out to the middle. Followed by Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood who walk to bat for West Indies. Suranga Lakmal to start with the ball.

Brilliant by the visitors! The spinners ran havoc with the ball. Veerasammy Permaul and Jomel Warrican went onto take nine wickets combined. This session truly belongs to the visitors. The onus now  comes on their batters to give a good reply and compliment a good effort of their bowlers. Stay tuned as they come back for the reply.

The hosts started off brilliantly with a 106-run opening stand. They lost their skipper on Day 1 itself. It was the only stand that had an impact on the game. Sri Lanka went onto add only 91 runs on Day 2 and were bundled out for 204 runs. This tells you the story of the innings.

OUT! BOWLED! A peach of a delivery to get rid of the injured Angelo Mathews! Most of the batters would have found it hard to negotiate this beauty! Tossed up, around middle, and turning away just that little bit. Mathews prods to block, does not get to the pitch of the ball due to his hamstring and he misses. The ball spins past his blade and rattles his off pole. Sri Lanka are bundled out for 204.
FOUR! SMASHED! Loopy ball, in the slot, around off. Angelo Mathews gets to the pitch of the ball and smokes it past the bowler. The ball races away to the fence.
Fuller in length, around off. Angelo Mathews blocks it out watchfully.
Tossed up, on off. Praveen Jayawickrama blocks it.
Who will walk out now? It is Praveen Jayawickrama.

OUT! TAKEN! Veerasammy Permaul gets a five-wicket haul and Sri Lanka lose their ninth wicket now! Loopy ball, outside off, inviting the batter to slog. Lakmal sees the flight and looks to go downtown but gets a thick outside edge which goes towards Jomel Warrican at backward point and he takes a simple catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Jomel Warrican b Veerasammy Permaul

Commentary.Commentary: An appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire. Fuller in length, around off. Suranga Lakmal prods to block this one. It was clearly off the bat. Maybe the sound was of the bat hitting the pad.
Darted on the pads. Suranga Lakmal clears his front leg and defends it.
Flatter ball, outside off. Suranga Lakmal cuts it to point.
Loopy ball, on off. Suranga Lakmal blocks it out.
SIX! AND AGAIN! Loopy ball, around middle. Angelo Mathews middles this one as he smacks it over long on for another maximum!

SIX! BANG! Just over the long on fielder! Tossed up, around middle. Angelo Mathews clears his front leg and lofts it towards long on. The fielder in the deep jumps but the ball goes just over him for a biggie.
Fuller in length, around off. Angelo Mathews drives it hard to long off.
Just short of the long off fielder! Tossed up, outside off. Angelo Mathews lofts it towards long off.
Another ball, fuller in length, around off. Angelo Mathews strokes it to long on.
Loopy ball, around off. Angelo Mathews drills it to long off but does not run!
A tad short, outside off. Suranga Lakmal looks to cut yet again but gets and underedge towards backward point.
Flatter ball, just outside off. Suranga Lakmal stays back to cut but does not get any bat on it.
On a length, around middle. Suranga Lakmal blocks it out.
Shorter in length, outside off. Angelo Mathews drags it to long off and hops towards the other end. He is clearly struggling with his hamstring here!
Flatter ball, outside off. Angelo Mathews cuts it to cover.

Who will walk out now? It is Angelo Mathews who walk out to at now. He was injured and got off the field to nurse himself, but the rest of the batters could not negotiate well and Mathews has to come back and get his team out of trouble here.

OUT! BOWLED! Permaul is on a roll here at Galle! He hurls a full ball, around middle. Lasith Embuldeniya stays inside the line of the ball and looks to work it towards cover-point but he misses and the ball crashes onto his stumps. What a comeback this has been from West Indies!
BEATEN! Drift and turn for Warrican! Tossed up, around off, turning away late. Suranga Lakmal prods to defend but the ball spins past his outside edge.
Ohhh Nooo! A huge dark cloud is hovering around the ground. Let's hope it does not pour down and passes by with the help of the wind. All we want is a good day of Test cricket.
On a length, outside off. Suranga Lakmal blocks it off the front foot.
Darted on the pads. Suranga Lakmal clips it to wide of mid-wicket and collects a couple.
Flatter ball, around off. Suranga Lakmal defends it off the front foot.
Tossed up, on off. Suranga Lakmal blocks it out.
FOUR! Width on offer and Lakmal pounces on it! Too short, outside off. Suranga Lakmal rocks back and cuts it past point for a boundary.
Floated, on a length, outside off. Lasith Embuldeniya skips down and works it to mid off.
Tossed up, on a length, outside off. Lasith Embuldeniya smothers the spin nicely and pushes it to mid off.
Tossed up, down leg. Suranga Lakmal turns it to the leg side and rotates the strike.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Suranga Lakmal looks to cut but it goes off the inner half towards cover.
Turn and bounce! Floated, around middle and turning down leg. Lasith Embuldeniya chips it to wide of the leg slip fielder for a single.
Flatter ball, outside off. Suranga Lakmal stays back and cuts it to cover-point for a run.
Fuller in length, around off. Lasith Embuldeniya blocks it out watchfully.
Tossed up, on a length, around off. Lasith Embuldeniya looks to defend but gets the inside edge which falls just wide of Nkrumah Bonner at short leg.
Flatter ball, around off. Lasith Embuldeniya blocks it off the front foot.
Lasith Embuldeniya comes out at number 9.

OUT! TAKEN! A very soft dismissal and Sri Lanka slip further! Flatter ball, around off, turning away late. Ramesh Mendis looks to flick it to the leg side against the turn but closes the bat face early. The ball takes the leading edge and goes straight to Shai Hope at cover who takes a dolly.
Commentary.Howout: c Shai Hope b Jomel Warrican

Commentary.Commentary: Full and on off. Mendis blocks it out.
On off, Mendis pushes it to mid off.
On the pads, Mendis tucks it to square leg for a single.
Floated, full and outside out. The ball turns away. Mendis leaves it alone.
Full and on off. Mendis goes for the sweep again. This time it hits Nkrumah Bonner on his shin pads and short leg and saves a boundary.
FOUR! Now Mendis gets off the mark with a boundary. Full and on off. Mendis gets low and sweeps it through square leg. His shot almost gets the square leg umpire. The ball races away to the fence.
Tossed up, on off. Mendis defends it out solidly.
Flatter and on off. Mendis stays back and punches it to point.
FOUR! All runs coming from this point are crucial for the hosts. Short and on off. Lakmal stays back and pulls it over mid-wicket for a boundary. A poor delivery to end a good over by Warrican.
Slower through the air, around off. Lakmal prods and looks to defend it out. The ball turns away and beats the outside edge.
Full and on off. Lakmal presses forward and defends it out.
Suranga Lakmal is the new man in.

Review time! Dinesh Chandimal has opted for a review after having adjudged LBW by the umpire. There is nothing on the UltraEdge and the Ball Tracker indicates three reds. Chandimal will have to take the walk back to the pavilion.

OUT! LBW! Jomel Warrican strikes and gets his second wicket. Full, around middle and leg. Dinesh Chandimal gets low and looks to sweep it away but misses. The ball sneaks under the blade and raps him on the pads. Jomel Warrican appeals and the umpire raises his finger. Dinesh Chandimal opts for the review. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows three reds and the batter has to trudge back to the pavilion.

Oh Dear! Joshua Da Silva will be unhappy that he put his gloves in between. Looped up, full and on off. The ball turns away. Dinesh Chandimal looks to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge. Joshua Da Silva pushes his hand to the right and looks to grab it but the ball defelects and goes to the off side. It was an easy catch for the slip fielder.
DROPPED! Full and on off. Dinesh Chandimal looks to defend it out. The ball turns away. The ball takes the outside edge and goes towards first slip. The ball lands short of the fielder.
Ramesh Mendis walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT! Simple catch to short leg and the spinners are working their magic for the visitors. Veerasammy Permaul picks up his third wicket. Looped up, around off. The ball grips and turns in. Charith Asalanka prods and looks to defend it out. The ball takes the inside edge, goes onto the pads and lobs towards short leg. Nkrumah Bonner is stationed there and he takes a simple catch, with his eyes on the ball. Sri Lanka slip further.
Commentary.Howout: c Nkrumah Bonner b Veerasammy Permaul

Commentary.Commentary: On the pads, Asalanka tucks it to square leg.
Around off. Asalanka comes inside the line and nudges it to square leg.
Flatter and on off. Asalanka blocks it to short leg fielder.
Looped up, full and outside off. Asalanka continues to remain solid in his defense.
Full and outside off. Asalanka prods and blocks it out.
Floated, around off. Chandimal punches it through covers for a couple of runs. Easy pickings.

Short and around off. Asalanka goes back and punches it through covers for a single. A poor delivery to follow with. This has been the weak-point of the West Indies bowlers. They have failed to maintain the pressure.
FOUR! The debutant is looking confident. Full, around middle and leg. Asalanka lunges forward and slog-sweeps it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Tossed up, full and on off. Asalanka blocks it towards point off the outer half.
Full and on off. Asalanka presses forward and blocks it to the off side.
A dot now! Chase comes around the wicket. Full and angled into leg. Asalanka defends it back to the bowler.
Roston Chase (13-0-57-1) comes back to bowl.
Full and on off. Chandimal keeps it out.
On off, Dinesh Chandimal blocks it out.
Full, around middle and off. Chandimal defends it out solidly.

Angelo Mathews seems to be struggling with his hamstring! The Sri Lankan physio is out in the middle to have a look at him. The umpires decide to have a Drinks break. West Indies have been top notch right from the word go on Day 2 and they have caused some serious problems to the Lankan batters. The hosts badly need a partnership if they are post a good first innings total. Oh, dear! It seems nothing is going Sri Lanka's way! Angelo Mathews has walked off the field and Dinesh Chandimal has come out to bat now.
Floated, around middle. The ball turns in. Asalanka stays back and flicks it towards fine leg. The batters take a single.
A single now! Tossed up, full and outside off. Mathews pushes it through covers for a single.
Full and around off. Charith Asalanka looks to push it towards cover. The ball takes the inside edge and onto the pads.

NO BALL! Flatter and on off. Mathews goes back and punches it through covers. The batters cross for a single. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps. He has to reload the final delivery.
Looped up, full and on off. Mathews blocks it out.
Full and on off. Mathews blocks it out.
Full and on off. Mathews defends it out watchfully.
Tossed up, on off. Mathews blocks it out.
On off, Mathews defends it off his front foot.

FOUR! Charith Asalanka gets off the mark in some fashion. Full and on off. Charith Asalanka reverse sweeps it through square leg. The ball races away to the fence. As soon as the keeper says the shot. He continues being chirpy and say's it is time for some T20 action now.
On off, Asalanka watchfully watches it out.
The debutant, Charith Asalanka walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Brilliant work by Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps. Veerasammy Permaul picks up his second wicket of the over. What a turnaround. Flatter, outside off. Dhananjaya de Silva stays back and looks to have a poke at it, he was very late into his shot. The ball takes the outside edge. Joshua Da Silva keeps his palms behind, but the ball lobs in front off him. He keeps his eyes on the ball and takes a one handed catch to complete his task. Brilliant from the visitors.
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Veerasammy Permaul

Dhananjaya de Silva is the new man in.

Pathum Nissanka asks the non-striker if he thinks it is needed to go upstairs but Mathews thinks it is not needed and Nissanka has to depart after a great knock.

Flatter ball, on a length, around off. Angelo Mathews blocks it out.

Fuller in length, around off. Angelo Mathews steps out and clips it to wide of mid on for a run.

Tossed up, around off, turning in sharply. Angelo Mathews blocks it out.
Flatter ball, turning down leg. Pathum Nissanka clips it behind square on the leg side for a single.

We are set for the action to begin! The West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Pathum Nissanka and Oshada Fernando who come out to bat for Sri Lanka. Chase to complete his over.

PITCH REPORT - Farveez Maharoof is down for the pitch report. He says that it is pretty hot. Adds that the wicket looks very dry. Tells that spinners will come into play early on in the day and feels that it looks more like a  Day 3 pitch.

Mickey Arthur is down for a chat. He says he has enjoyed his time here. The warmth of the island, it is a beautiful country. Adds that he enjoys building team and when Sri Lanka approached they had a lot of work to do and he is glad about his work. Mentions, it is difficult when you part ways with a side, but the relationship goes on and he says, he will keep an eye out on all the players.

West Indies failed to cause any trouble to the batters. It was a persistent pace attack to start with from both ends. Roach and Holder probed good lines and lengths but could not find any success and the batters negotiated the new ball really well. Kraigg Brathwaite then got Mayers into the mix, along with Chase and Warrican. The spinners though caused some trouble with some turn and extra bounce. It was Chase who drew the first blood and an important one of Karunaratne. West Indies will come out and look to pick wickets at regular intervals to put a lid on the scoring rate.

Sri Lankan openers scored at a brisk rate in the time they spent on the field. This time Pathum Nissanka was the aggressor, unlike the first game where Dimuth Karunaratne was the one who had his foot on the gas. The pair stitched a 106-run stand before the skipper made his way back in the hut. After the wicket, the run flow slowed down. Fernando struggled a bit against the spinners, but to his benefit the umpires suspended the game due to bad light and only 34.4 overs were bowled out of the scheduled 45. Nissanka is still out in the middle at 61 not out. The hosts will hope the pair come back out and continue the good work.

The rain gods had their say on Day 1 of the second Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies. The first two sessions went down the drain without even getting done with the toss. We saw some cricket in the final session. Sri Lanka elected to bat and went back as the happier side at Stumps on Day 1. On that note, welcome to the coverage of Day 2 of the second Test match.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

That is all from Day 1 of the second Test between Sri Lanka and West Indies! Day 2 will commence early and the live action begins at 0945 local time (0415 GMT) but you can join us in advance for the build-up. We hope that rain gods stay away tomorrow and we get to see a full day of riveting Test cricket. Cheers!

West Indies bowlers were very inconsistent with their lines and lengths and gave away too many freebies to Sri Lanka's opening batters. Kemar Roach and Jason Holder did start well but they failed to get the breakthrough. Jomel Warrican kept things tight in the middle and hit the right areas to keep the batters in check. Roston Chase did get the priced wicket of Dimuth Karunaratne but he was a touch expensive and dished out a lot of loose balls. All in all, it wasn't the best of bowling performances from the visitors but they would look to bounce back on the second day of this Test and pull things back in their favour.

Sri Lankan openers Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka were brilliant once again as they stitched together a stand of 106 runs before the skipper perished. Young Pathum Nissanka has looked solid yet again and he continues to impress one and all. He negotiated the new ball pretty well along with Dimuth Karunaratne and looked equally good against spin as well. Karunaratne also looked soild until he was at the crease but fell cheaply to Roston Chase just minutes before the umpires called it a day. The Lankans, however would be happy with the way they have fared after having won the toss and opted to bat first and their batters would look to capitalize on the start that they have got now.

Right then! Only 34.4 overs were possible on Day 1 of the second Test, due to rain and bad light and Sri Lanka have managed to score 113 runs with the loss of just 1 wicket. West Indies would be a touch disappointed with their bowling effort as they were not upto the mark and gave away too many loose balls to the Lankan batters.

Full and on off. Nissanka plays it back to the bowler.
Oshada Fernando walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! Chase gets his man this time. The skipper could not replicate his innings from the first Test match. He goes back to hut on 42. This has brought delight to the bowler and it means a lot to the West Indies side, after what they went through in the first game. Chase draws the first blood. Looped up, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne chips it back to the bowler. Chase keeps his eyes on the ball, moves to his right and holds the ball cleanly. Joshua Da Silva roars loudly after Chase completes the catch.
Looped up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out to the off side off the outer half.
FOUR! Freebie for Dimuth Karunaratne. Full toss, on middle and off. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it through mid-wicket and bags a boundary.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it out.
FOUR! Nicely played.100-run partnership comes up for the pair. Short ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne goes on the back foot and punches it past backward point. The ball goes to the boundary.
Short and on leg. Nissanka stays back and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Flatter ball, on off. Pathum Nissanka looks to defend but the ball takes the outside edge and goes past the slip fielder. A single taken!
Fuller in length, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne nudges it to wide of mid on and collects a single.
Tossed up, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods and pushes it to cover.
Loopy ball, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it back to the bowler.

A stumping chance goes begging! Tossed up, well outside off, turning in late. Dimuth Karunaratne shimmies down and looks to slog but he misses and gets hit on his pad. The ball rolls away to the keeper but Joshua Da Silva fails to grab it cleanly and Dimuth Karunaratne survives!
Another full toss, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne skips down and flicks it to mid-wicket.

DRINKS! The opening pair of Sri Lanka, is off to a great start yet again in this series. The West Indies bowlers have not yet caused any major trouble to this pair. They will hope to break this stand before the Stumps on Day 1.
Loopy ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne presses forward and tucks it to wide of mid-wicket for a single.
Flatter ball, on a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods but leaves it alone.
A full toss, just outside off. Nissanka shimmies down and eases it to long on for a run.
Fuller in length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne drives it past cover and takes one.
Tossed up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks this one out.
Flatter ball, turning in sharply from middle. Pathum Nissanka tucks it behind square on the leg side for a single.
Another ball, fuller in length, around off. Pathum Nissanka drills it towards long off to keep the strike for the next over.
On a length, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne eases it to long on for a run.
A tad short, outside off. Pathum Nissanka rocks back and cuts it to point for a single.
Flatter ball, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it off the front foot.
Fuller in length, around off. Pathum Nissanka skips down and works it to mid off.
A juicy full toss, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne skips down and heaves it towards deep mid-wicket. A single taken.
Flatter ball, around middle, turning in sharply. Pathum Nissanka tucks it to short fine leg.
Tossed up, on a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne drills it to long off for a single.
Flatter ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
FOUR! A half-tracker, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne rocks back and cuts it past cover to collect a boundary.

In the air, just short of the fielder! Tossed up, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to flick, closes the face of his bat early and it takes the leading edge which falls short of the cover fielder.
Tossed up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods to defend this one out.
Roston Chase (3-0-10-0) is back into the attack.
Loopy ball, on a length, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it out.
Flatter ball, way outside off. Pathum Nissanka stays back and lets it through to the keeper.
Tossed up, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it out watchfully.
BEATEN! Flatter ball, on a length, around off, turning away just a little bit! Pathum Nissanka looks to block but the ball zips past his outside edge.
Tossed up, around off. Pathum Nissanka presses forward and blocks it.
Floated, on a length, around off. Pathum Nissanka skips out and pushes it to cover.
Flatter ball, outside off, turning back in sharply. Dimuth Karunaratne hangs back and shoulders arms to this one.
Fuller in length, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne steps out and works it to mid on.
Floated, on a length, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it off the front foot.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Pathum Nissanka stays back and cuts it to point for a single.
Nicely tossed up, outside off, turning away sharply. Pathum Nissanka lets it be.
Flatter ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne rocks back and slices it past point for a single.
Another ball, fuller in length, around off. Pathum Nissanka presses forward and is solid in his defence.
Flighted delivery, around off. Pathum Nissanka prods to block this one out.
Floated, around middle. Pathum Nissanka skips down and pushes it to mid off.
Flatter ball, on a length, around middle. Pathum Nissanka defends it solidly.
Tossed up, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks this one out.
BEATEN! Tossed up, on a length, around off, turning away late. Pathum Nissanka looks to defend but the ball spins past his outside edge.
FIFTY FOR Pathum Nissanka! A top innings from him so far but he would be aware that the job is only half done! Floated, on a length, around off. Nissanka works it to long off for a run.
Tossed up, around off. Nissanka blocks it out.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Pathum Nissanka cuts it behind square on the off side for a couple of runs.
Flatter ball, around off. Pathum Nissanka pushes it to cover.
Tossed up, on a length, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it off the front foot.
Tossed up, on middle. Dimuth Karunaratne skips down and works it to mid on for a run.
Looped up, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne eases it down to long off for a single.
Touch short and outside off. Karunaratne stays back and cuts it to point, but cannot find the gap this time.
Tossed up, around off. The ball turns in. Nissanka stays back and tucks it to square leg for a single.
Full and on off. Nissanka comes forward and flicks it to short mid-wicket.
Flighted, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne works it towards long off for a single.
Looped up, around middle and leg. The ball turns in a bit. Nissanka flicks it towards fine leg for a single.
Just a tad short, outside off. Pathum Nissanka cuts it towards cover point and takes a run.
Tossed up, on a length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka drives it to mid off.
Permaul sees Nissanka skipping down so he drags his length back, around middle. Pathum Nissanka blocks it out.
Flatter and quicker, outside off. Pathum Nissanka lets it be.
Tossed up, around off. Pathum Nissanka defends it off the front foot.
Flatter ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka cuts it to point.
Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods and defends it into the pitch. A good over by Chase. He goes some turn and bounce which looked to trouble the Sri Lankan skipper.

FOUR! Poor delivery. Full and on leg. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it through mid-wicket. The ball races away. Kyle Mayers gives it a chase and tries to pull it back near the ropes but his forward momentum does not get the ball back and it touches the rope. A boundary.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it to cover.
Tossed up, around off. The ball gets some extra bounce off the surface. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it to the leg side off the inside edge.
Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it watchfully.
OH! Close! Looped up, around middle and leg. The ball turns away. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and looks to defend it out but misses. The ball goes off the pads to the off side.
Outside off, Nissanka leaves it alone for the keeper.
NO BALL! Veerasammy Permaul oversteps and the umpire signals a no ball. On leg, Nissanka tucks it to square leg.
Tossed up, outside off. The ball turns away. Nissanka prods and looks to defend it out but gets beaten.
SIX! BANG! Excellent use of the feet. Pathum Nissanka launches himself. Full and outside off. Pathum Nissanka gets to the pitch of the ball and smokes it over the long off fence for a maximum.
Full and on off. Nissanka pushes it to cover.
Loopy ball, around off. The ball turns away. Nissanka looks to defend it out but gets beaten by the turn. Nicely bowled.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it to cover for a single.
Full and on off. Nissanka works it to short leg off the inner half, as he looks to defend it out.
Loopy ball, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it to the off side for a single.
Touch short and on off. This time the ball turns away. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it back to the bowler.

Chase comes around the wicket for the left hander. Floated, outside off. The ball goes not turn away. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms, hoping it will turn away, but it spins straight through and goes past the off pole.
Tossed up, on off. Nissanka comes forward and pushes it to the left of long on for a single.
Floated, full and on off. The ball turns in a bit. Nissanka stays back and tucks it to the leg side.
Roston Chase comes to bowl.
Full, around middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it towards square leg. The fielder was quick to get to the ball.
Looped up, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne puts his front leg across and defends the ball out with his pads.

EDGY! A bit of turn now for Veerasammy Permaul. Looped up, full and on off. The ball turns away. Nissanka looks to push it to the off side. The ball takes the outside edge and goes past the slip fielder towards third man. The fielder gives it a chase and stops it from touching the ropes in the deep. The batters pick three.
Quicker, full and on off. Nissanka defends it out watchfully.
Flighted, full and on middle. Nissanka pushes it to cover.
Looped up, full and on off. Nissanka dabs it to cover.
Veerasammy Permaul is into the attack now.
Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne drives it towards mid off. He has not been able to find the gaps in this game so far.
Fuller, on the pads. Nissanka flicks it through square leg for a single.
On off, Nissanka blocks it out watchfully.
Good-length ball, around off. Nissanka hops and punches it through covers. The batters take two before the fielder cuts it out.

FOUR! Nissanka continues to find boundaries. This one was a gorgeous straight drive, could not have asked for a much better shot. Full length, on off. Nissanka drives it down the ground. The ball goes into the boundary at long on. No stopping that one. With this boundary, the 50 run partnership comes up for the pair.
Nicely bowled! Full-length ball, on off. The ball jags in a bit and stays pretty low. Nissanka gets his blade down in time and blocks it out.
Length and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne presses forward and defends it to cover with full face of the blade.
Swing and a miss! A length ball, wide outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne reaches out and looks to push it through point but misses. The ball bounces over the blade.
On a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms.
FOUR! Dimuth Karunaratne gets his second boundary off Kyle Mayers. Full length, on middle and off. Dimuth Karunaratne gets his wrists into the play and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Good-length ball, angling across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne comes towards the line and shoulders his arms.
Fuller, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne comes forward and tucks it towards mid on.

DRINKS! The first hour belongs to the hosts! Sri Lankan openers Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka have negotiated the new ball pretty well and managed to get their team off to a decent start! Windies bowlers have lacked consistency and they haven't been able to put the opposition's openers under pressure!
Good-length ball, outside off. The ball nips away and gets some elevation off the deck. Nissanka shoulders his arms to this one. A maiden over for Holder.
Full-length ball and around off. Nissanka presses forward and defends it out.
Full and outside off. Pathum Nissanka comes towards the line and defends it out with soft hands. The ball takes the outside edge and goes to the man at second slip on a bounce.
On a length, outside off. Nissanka leaves it alone yet again, as he shoulders his arms.
Good-length ball, outside off. The ball nips away off the deck. Pathum Nissanka shoulders his arms and leaves it for the keeper.
On a length, around off. Nissanka stays inside the crease and defends it to cover.
Nice movement on this one! Beaten! A length ball, outside off. The ball nips away. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
A length ball, outside off, angling across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out solidly off the front foot.
On a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne taps it to point.
FOUR! Put Away! Back of a length, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back, swivels and pulls it through square leg for a boundary. Not a good start by Kyle Mayers.
A length ball, on the pads. Nissanka nudges it towards square leg and gets a single this time.

FOUR! Nicely played! Nissanka welcomes Mayers into the attack in some fashion. Full and on off. It was a juicy half-volley for the batsman. Nissanka opens the face of the bat at the last moment and drives it through covers for a boundary.
Kyle Mayers comes to bowl.
A length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne has no shot to offer this time.
Fuller, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it to deep mid-wicket. The fielder fumbles and the batters take two runs comfortably.
Length, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out.

BEATEN! What a beauty! Jason Holder comes around the wicket. He serves a length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne sees the width on offer and goes for the drive. The ball though straightens a bit after hitting the deck. Dimuth Karunaratne gets beaten, as the ball zips past the outside edge.
Fuller delivery, on leg stump. Nissanka stays back and flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Back of a length, outside off. Nissanka watches it sail past him and into the keeper's mitts.
Another good over by Roach comes to an end! Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms.
Fuller, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne comes on the front foot and pushes it towards mid off.
A length ball, outside off, jagging back in. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms.
Comes back in sharply! Good-length ball, outside off. The ball nips in off the deck. Dimuth Karunaratne stays inside the crease and lets it go to the keeper.
Fuller, on off. Nissanka presses forward and looks to defend it to the off side. The ball takes the inside edge and goes towards deep square leg. The batters cross for a single.
A full-length ball, nipping in a bit. Pathum Nissanka stays back and defends it out watchfully. West Indies still persisting with the fast bowlers.
Fuller in length, way outside off, holding its line. Dimuth Karunaratne does not bother playing at it.
Short of a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
Good-length ball, around middle, jagging back in. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto his pad.
BEAUTY! Length ball, around the fourth stump channel, shaping away late. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend but the ball whistles past his outside edge.
Fuller in length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka looks to drive but loses the grip on his bat and gets the toe end of his bat as the ball goes over the cover fielder. The batters cross for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Pathum Nissanka sits back and blocks it to the off side.
Length ball, way outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it through to the keeper.
Short of a length, around off, holding its line and bouncing after landing. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it awkwardly off the back foot.
Back of a length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders arms to this one.
Fuller in length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to drive but it goes off the inner half of the blade towards mid on.
Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne presses forward but does not offer any shot to it.
Length ball, way outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
Length ball, around off. Pathum Nissanka prods to defend but gets a thick outside edge which goes past the second slip fielder. Jermaine Blackwood gives it a chase and the batters take two.

Review! Kraigg Brathwaite takes the review for lbw. The on-field decision is NOT OUT. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows the ball is missing the wickets. West Indies lose a review here. The on-field decision stands.

NOT OUT! West Indies lose a review as well! Back of a length, around middle, jagging back in sharply. Nissanka looks to block but he misses and gets hit high on his pad. Holder puts in an appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Kraigg Brathwaite opts for a review but the Ball Tracker confirms that the ball was going well down leg so the on-field decision stays.
Length ball, around the fifth stump line. Pathum Nissanka prods to block this one but gets a thick outside edge which runs past the slip cordon. The slip fielder gives it a chase and keeps it to two.
Back of a length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka stands tall, rides the bounce nicely and punches it past covers for a couple of runs.
Back of a length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka punches it off the back foot towards cover.
Short of a length, just outside off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it off the back foot.
Back of a length, well outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
Length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders arms to this one.
Fuller in length, way outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne does not bother playing at that!
Length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne drives it towards mid off.
That came back in sharply! Good-length ball, around off and jagging back in. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend but he gets an inside edge onto his pad.
Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it through to the keeper.
Length ball, around off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it off the back foot.
BEATEN! Good-length ball, angling in from outside off and then shaping away just that little bit. Nissanka looks to block it off the front foot but the ball zips past his outside edge.
Back of a length, around leg. Dimuth Karunaratne clips it behind square on the leg side for a run.
Length ball, angling in from middle. Pathum Nissanka looks to block but gets an inside edge towards fine leg. A single taken!
Good-length ball, around off. Pathum Nissanka stays back and dabs it into the deck with soft hands.
Short of a length, way outside off. Pathum Nissanka hangs back and leaves it alone.
Overpitched ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne squeezes it out towards cover.
Another ball, fuller in length, around the fifth stump. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it through to the keeper.
Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and shoulders arms to this one.
Full ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods and drives it towards mid off.
Length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it through to the keeper.
Good-length ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka sits back and steers it to third man for a run.
Fuller in length, way outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
Leg bye! Back of a length, around leg. Pathum Nissanka looks to nudge it to the leg side but misses and gets hit on his thigh pad. The ball rolls away to the leg side for a leg bye!
Length ball, angling in from outside off. Pathum Nissanka does not offer any shot to this one.
Another ball, around the fifth stump. Pathum Nissanka prods but shoulders arms to this one.
Much better from Holder! Good-length ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka lets it be.
FOUR LEG BYES! Back of a length, around leg. Pathum Nissanka misses his flick and the ball brushes his thigh pad before going into the fine leg fence.
On a length, around middle and leg. Pathum Nissanka turns it to wide of mid-wicket for a single.

Top effort from Nkrumah Bonner to save a run for his side! Fuller in length, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne drives it past cover-point. Bonner gives it a chase, slides and keeps the ball in play just in front of the ropes. The batters take three runs.
Good-length ball, jagging back in from middle. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it watchfully.
Length ball, darted on the pads. Pathum Nissanka clips it to fine leg for a run.
FOUR! Edged and boundary! Good-length ball, around the fifth stump channel. Pathum Nissanka prods to defend but gets the outside edge which runs past the slip cordon and into the third man fence.
Good-length ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka leaves it alone.
Good-length ball, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne gets behind the line of the ball to block this one out.
Fuller in length, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne jams it out towards mid on.
Length ball, around the fourth stump, curling away with the angle. Dimuth Karunaratne prods but leaves it alone in the end.
Good-length ball, jagging back in from middle. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it off the front foot.
Length ball, around leg. Pathum Nissanka tucks it behind square on the leg side for a run.
FOUR! Glorious! Nissanka greets Holder with a classical straight drive! A half-volley, around off. Nissanka presses forward and drives it past the bowler to collect a boundary.
Jason Holder to bowl from the other end.
Length ball, way outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it through to the keeper.

Sri Lanka and Pathum Nissanka are up and running! Good-length ball, around the fourth stump channel. Nissanka pushes it to the left of the cover fielder. Roston Chase there fails to collect the ball cleanly and concedes a single.
Good-length ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka shoulders arms to this one.
Fuller in length, just outside off. Pathum Nissanka drives but straight to the cover fielder.
Back of a length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka stays back and defends it off the back foot.
Roach starts with a length ball, outside off. Pathum Nissanka blocks it solidly off the front foot.

The game is set to begin. The West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka who walk out to bat for Sri Lanka. Before the game gets underway, the West Indies players take the knee to show their support for the BLM movement. While, the Sri Lankan batters stand tall and pay respects. Kemar Roach to start with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 1, Session 3 ...

Kraigg Brathwaite, the skipper of West Indies, is in for a chat. He says, there are two changes Roach and Permaul make their way in place of Gabriel and Cornwall. He says, he is happy with three spinners and have a couple more options. Ends by saying it is going to be a mental challenge, to come back from the last defeat.

Dimuth Karunaratne, the skipper of Sri Lanka, says they will bat first. Adds that it is a pretty good wicket and it will turn on the fourth and the fifth day. Tells that they have made change, Charith Asalanka comes in for Dushmantha Chameera. Says that it is good to have three spinners and he does not have any problem with it.

PITCH REPORT – Aamir Sohail is near the deck. He says, the pitch is lighter in colour than the previous game. Adds, the spinners will be on the attack straightaway. The batters will have a lot of problem to negotiate it well. Ends by wishing luck to the fast bowlers.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), Jermaine Blackwood, Shai Hope, Nkrumah Bonner, Roston Chase, Kyle Mayers, Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Veerasammy Permaul (In for Rahkeem Cornwall), Jomel Warrican, Kemar Roach (In for Shannon Gabriel).

Sri Lanka (Playing XI) - Dimuth Karunaratne (C), Pathum Nissanka, Oshada Fernando, Dhananjaya de Silva, Angelo Mathews, Charith Asalanka (In for Dushmantha Chameera), Dinesh Chandimal (WK), Ramesh Mendis, Suranga Lakmal, Lasith Embuldeniya, Praveen Jayawickrama.

West Indies' batters did show some resistance in the first Test but they failed in the spin Test of Sri Lanka. Windies' bowlers came back well in the first innings but their batters were not able to bat long and put the opposition under pressure. Nkrumah Bonner was their standout performer in the second innings who fought hard along with Joshua Da Silva but the visitors fell short by a big margin in the end. Kraigg Brathwaite would hope that they come out with intent in this Test if they are to level the series 1-1. They have their task cut out as they face another spin challenge at Galle and it will be interesting to see the reply of the visitors' batters whilst the series is on the line. Also, rain is predicted on the first couple of days but we hope that it stays away and we get to see full day's action. Stay tuned for toss and further updates.

Sri Lanka are a tough opponent to beat at their own backyard and they proved it against West Indies in the first Test. Their skipper, Dimuth Karunaratne led from the front in the first Test who was well backed up by Sri Lanka's quality spinners in Lasith Embuldeniya, Ramesh Mendis and Praveen Jayawickrama to draw first blood in this two-match Test series. Not to forget the vital contribution of Sri Lanka's experinced players in Angelo Mathews and Dinesh Chandimal who played crucial knocks when their side needed them the most. The hosts would be high on confidence coming into the second Test and they would be eager to keep up their good work in order to seal the series 2-0. Also, this will be the last Test match for Mickey Arthur as Sri Lanka's Head Coach and Dimuth Karunaratne and his men would be keen to give their coach a grand send off.

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 1 of the 2nd Test between Sri Lanka and West Indies which is set to commence at the iconic Galle Stadium. The first Test saw the hosts handing a comprehensive defeat to West Indies and thereby going 1-0 up in the two-match Test series. The visitors would be keen to make a comeback in this Test as not only is the series on the line but also World Test Championship points are up for grab.
...Day 1, Session 1...
We are back for Sri Lanka's second innings! The players of West Indies stride out to the middle. Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka are at the crease! Veerasammy Permaul will start with the ball.

Right then. Sri Lanka have their work cut out for them as they need 49 to cut the deficit and they will look to come out and get past the lead number quickly. The Windies will want to start with a couple of wickets early on, so that the pressure will be on the hosts. Join us for Sri Lanka's second innings in a bit.

It was all about the spinners for the Lankans. They took their time to get the first two wickets and failed to extract a lot from the deck early on, but once the second wicket fell, they smelt blood and bowled with a lot of zest and hunger and it is due to their efforts that they are only behind by 49 runs and not a number around the 100-run mark. Ramesh Mendis was the architect for the Lankans as he ended with 6 snares to his name and was also very lethal in dismantling the middle order of the Windies. Lasith Embuldeniya and Praveen Jayawickrama supported Mendis well too from the other end and had 2 wickets each to their name.

That spells the end of West Indies' first innings and they have a decent lead of 49 runs to their name. They would have wanted to get some more runs to their lead but this is by no means a bad lead to have. The start was a really good one by the Windies as Jermaine Blackwood and Kraigg Brathwaite raised a 62-run stand and then, Kraigg Brathwaite and Nkrumah Bonner had a good stand of 75 runs too, but once this stand was broken, the wickets kept tumbling along and from a position of 137/1, they slipped to 208/8. Mayers and Veerasammy Permaul did well to add valuable runs to their lead too with their stand of 38 runs and in the end, the Windies will be content with their work in this innings.

...DAY 3, SESSION 3...

Sri Lanka have bounced back strongly in the second session by picking up 6 wickets for 90 runs. Ramesh Mendis was their standout performer who grabbed a five-wicket haul and spun the Lankans back into this Test match. Their spinners kept things in check for the majority of the second session and now find themselves in a much better position than what one would have expected. Although, they have conceded a lead of 31 runs now and it is important for them that they bowl out the visitors as early as possible, as they cannot afford to leak more runs going ahead in the innings. Do join us for the last session which begins at 3.15 pm local (9.45 am GMT).

West Indies did start extremely well with the bat, thanks to a gritty knock from their skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite, and well-supported by Nkrumah Bonner and Jermaine Blackwood. However, once the visitors lost their set batters in Bonner and Brathwaite, they fell like a pack of cards and lost the momentum. Kyle Mayers somehow managed to hang in there and also punished loose balls. The visitors have got a first innings lead now but they will look to stretch it further into something substantial.

The game has moved at a rate of knots in the second session on Day 3 and it is the hosts who have dominated it big time. The Lankan spinners spun a web around the West Indies' batters and they were left with no answers out in the middle. Having said that, West Indies have a first innings lead and they would take that probably, especially on a tricky wicket like this.

Not a lot to be happy about for the Lankans but they will be pleased that they broke the stand between Bonner and Brathwaite as they were looking way too comfortable out in the middle. Early in the session, they were finding it hard to trouble the pair of the Windies batters but as the session went on, they started to slowly find their feet and the ball started doing some tricks as well. It was Ramesh Mendis who struck and got rid of Bonner and the spinners then made it hard for Hope to settle in too. Even Suranga Lakmal was making the ball move and there were signs of reverse swing on offer. Even though this has not been the best session for the hosts, the pitch seems to be offering more now and they would look to extract all that they can and snare a few quick wickets. The next session should be an exciting one. Do join us for the same at 12.40 pm local (7.10 am GMT).

What a brilliant session this has been for the Windies! While they did lose a wicket right towards the end of the session, it has been them who has ruled the roost so far as the deficit has now been cut down to just 59 runs. A total of 76 runs were scored in the first session and the visitors lost just one wicket. The overnight batters for them, Nkrumah Bonner and Kraigg Brathwaite started the day off in a fine manner as they were slow in the early exchanges but started getting comfortable as the session went on. They raised a 50-run stand too and the skipper got to his fifty as well. Looking at how things were going by, you would think they would coast to Lunch unscathed but Bonner was not able to survive and lost his wicket. After that, the duo of Kraigg Brathwaite and Shai Hope managed to see out a slightly nervy period and that meant that the Windies only lost a single wicket in the morning session. They will be hoping to continue in the same manner now.

PITCH REPORT - With only around 90 overs bowled in this Test, it does seem like we are heading into Day 2. There is going to be a lot of spin on offer on this deck and the batters should be wary of the same. The arm ball can cause a lot of damage and the batters should be ready to get ahead or stay on the back foot.

Joshua Da Silva is down for a chat. He says that he likes to have fun out in the middle. Adds that he loves to talk and cheer up the guys when he is keeping for his side. Tells that there are a lot of eyes on him when DRS comes into picture. Says that they are in a very good position and they need to put 350-plus score on board.

Sri Lanka started very strong on Day 1 but they gave away their momentum come the Day 2 as their batters fell like a pack of cards and were just somehow able to cross the 200-run mark. Their bowlers were denied an early breakthrough by Windies' openers although their spinners bowled their heart out. Praveen Jayawickrama took an important wicket of Blackwood and gave the Lankans something to cheer on Day 2. Dimuth Karunaratne and his men would hope that they make early inroads on Day 3 and make sure that the visitors do not get a lead in the first innings. The pitch is assisting spinners and the likes of Lasith Embuldeniya, Ramesh Mendis and Praveen Jayawickrama will need to bring their A game for their side in such a crunch situation.

West Indies would be happy with the way things have gone so far and they will certainly feel that they have their noses slightly ahead going into Day 3 of this Test. Their bowlers bounced back hard on Day 2 to restrict the Lankan batters to a score which could be considered just below par on a track like this and they were backed up well by Windies' openers Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood. Although the visitors lost Blackwood just before rain came in on Day 2, they have an able overnight batter in Nkrumah Bonner who showed great resistance in the first Test. Windies would hope that they bat long and get a substantial lead as first innings lead is going to be very vital and not to forget that batting last on this pitch isn't going to be a walk in the park.

Hello and welcome to Day 3 of the second Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies. First two days were rain curtailed and we hope that raingods stay away from Day 3, which is known to be a moving day in Test cricket. West Indies have made a strong comeback on Day 2 and they would hope that they build on their momentum going ahead in this Test match.

Right then. That brings the curtains down on Day 2 of this Test match. Rain has again decided to pour down and let it's presence be felt, which has robbed us of having a full day's play on Day 2. Nevertheless, we are always hopeful of positive things and maybe Day 3 will be a better one in terms of the weather. Do join us for the same at 0945 local (0415 GMT). Cheers!

West Indies openers, Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood negotiated the new ball quite well and they stitched together a partnership of 62 runs before the latter fell when Praveen Jayawickrama trapped him in front. Sri Lankan spinners did trouble Windies' batters but they would be reasonably happy with the way things went as far as their batting is concerned. They will now look to cut the deficit as quickly as possible as first innings lead is going to be very crucial on a track like this.

Sri Lankan batters looked in all sorts of trouble as they lost their overnight batters in quick succession and their middle order batters looked absolutely clueless in the middle. To rub salt on their wounds, their experienced campaigner in Angelo Mathews got injured and walked off the field. However, he came out to bat later on but he was struggling with his hamstring. Mathews did hit a few lusty blows in the end which helped Sri Lanka to cross the 200-run mark. No other batter made a significant contribution and they were bundled out for 204.

West Indies bowlers bounced back strongly in the first session and their spinners Veerasammy Permaul and Jomel Warrican spun their web on the Lankan batters. They bowled tight lines and lengths throughout and got their rewards. Permaul bagged his maiden five-wicket haul while Warrican picked 4 wickets. The Windies conceded just 91 runs on Day 2 and picked up 9 wickets to turn the game in their favour.

Right then! Another day where rain has played spoilsport but we were able to get close to 58 overs of play on Day 2 of this Test. It would be safe to say that the day belonged to the visitors who came roaring back and put the Lankans on the back foot.

What a session of cricket did we witness! The West Indies will come back and look to cut the deficit watchfully. Another riveting session awaits. Do join us at 1240 local time (0710 GMT) for the second session.

What a comeback by West Indies! Their spinners have spun a web around the batters and have strangled them. It was all about Veerasammy Permaul, he earned his recall and has managed to make it count. He comes back and picks up a five-wicket haul in the first innings itself. He has helped his side to roar back in the game. He was supported well by Jomel Warrican from the other end, as he picked up a four-wicket haul and bundled out the hosts for 204 runs. The West Indies batters came back for a reply, and just tried to see off the session with caution and remained unscathed. They would hope they don't replicate the Lankan innings and stay sharp in the middle.

The hosts lost their grip over the advantage! Nissanka and Fernando came out to bat at the start of the day. Both looked pretty solid in the middle. Not letting the spinners settle down. But unlike the first Test match, Da Silva was being very chirpy behind the wickets, which might have some impact on the batters for sure. Fernando was the first one to depart of the hosts and then they kept losing wickets in quick succession. Nissanka soon slipped out and could not make his way to a three digit figure. The middle order could not get to a start and the hosts were part of a collapse. Sri Lanka, then came back to take the field, they bowled 4 overs, with a pace and spin combination. They would look to come back from Lunch and get going from the word go.

West Indies are the happier side going back into Lunch on Day 2 without a doubt. The hosts were at a solid position at the beginning of the day with nine wickets in hands, but they could not capitalize on it and bundled out for just 204. They lost nine wickets in a single session. Also, it looks like the ground staff is getting the covers on as a precaution. Well, it was just a precaution, but it looks like the rain has arrived. It is pouring down and we hope it passes by before the break ends.

PITCH REPORT - HD Ackerman is down for the pitch report. He adds that the pitch looks quite good and since the pacers haven't bowled a lot, the footmarks are not that pronounced. Dhananjaya de Silva is down for a chat. He says this knock is maybe his best one. Adds that they wanted to be in the safe zone so he and Embuldeniya wanted to play out as many overs as possible. Hello and a warm welcome to the final day of what has been a fantastic game of Test cricket. Right then! Another day of Test cricket has just flown by and even though three results are still possible, it is highly unlikely that the visitors can win it from here. Sri Lanka have a big lead of 279 runs. A draw will seal the series and valuable points on the WTC table for them. West Indies will need a miracle to get those important points. Just like Day 4, the fifth and final day of the Test match will start at 9:45 am local (4:15 am GMT). Do join us for the live action. Till then goodbye and take care!

An under-par showing is what we can label the Windies bowling display as. Coming into Day 4, the visitors must have been the happier team but right from the off, their spinners were put under pressure. Roston Chase did provide them with a couple of big breakthroughs on either side of Lunch but the visitors failed to build on it. At the end of the second session, one felt like West Indies were crawling back into the match as their spinners got the hosts down to just 2 wickets remaining. The last session though proved to be the difference-maker as the lack of intent from the visitors was there to see and de Silva along with Embuldeniya, the number 10 batter piled on the misery. Veerasammy Permaul seemed to be the only bowler who bowled his heart out and deservingly picked up three wickets. Needing to win the Test match and being in a good position to do so, the visitors have let the match slip and now will have to play exceedingly well to save the match.

Sri Lanka started off Day 4, reeling at 46 for 2 and no one expected them to bat for the entirety of Day 4. But one needs to give credit where credit is due and the hosts have deserved to be on top of proceedings because their batters have shown grit and determination. Pathum Nissanka and Charith Asalanka were positive from the get-go and made a fast start before the latter got out. Nissanka reached a half-century but on the stroke of Lunch, he too was dismissed. After some wickets early in the second session, Dhananjaya de Silva took matters into his own hands and put on a show along with the tailenders, first with Ramesh Mendis, he stitched a 51-run stand and then an unreal and unbeaten stand of 107-runs with Lasith Embuldeniya. De Silva brought up a classy century and then surpassed 150 as well. Embuldeniya too impressed highly with the bat and the hosts stretched their lead to 279 runs.

Yet another fascinating day of Test cricket comes to an end and the pendulum truly swung both ways today. What a session for the visitors! The spinners spun a web around the batters and scalped three wickets in this session to get their side back in the hunt. Roach picked a wicket early into the second session. Then, a partnership was built in the middle, and it looked as if the hosts will take the game away with a good lead, but just before the new ball was available, Brathwaite struck to get rid of Mendis and broke a crucial stand. Then it was all about the second new ball, Permaul rolled his fingers really well and picked up two wickets in no time and took his side ahead in the game.

This session was anchored by Dhananjaya de Silva! After losing a wicket at the stroke of Lunch, Sri Lanka needed the new pair to get a handy partnership which should be big enough to get them to a big lead, but Chandimal fell pretty early on to Chase. Mathews did not come out to bat, as he has been nursing his calf injury, which got Mendis into the middle. He stitched an important stand along with de Silva of 51 runs but slipped out in the final half-hour of the session. Lakmal joined de Silva later and hung around for a while but got rapped plumb in front of the stumps. Finally, Mathews came in limping, he was not at his best, but his team needed him. He went back only on a single, he was expected to score heavily but that wasn’t the case.

Beaten! Loopy ball, outside off. Lasith Embuldeniya puts in a stride to block but the ball goes straight and beats the outside edge.
Lasith Embuldeniya is in at number 10.

OUT! TAKEN! What a fantastic catch that is! Loopy ball, on off. Mathews is not able to reach the pitch of the ball while looking to block and gets the outside edge. Jermaine Blackwood dives to his right at first slip and takes a sharp low catch.

Commentary.Commentary: Shorter ball, on off. Pushed to covers.
Full ball, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on off. De Silva blocks it off the front foot.
Loopy ball, on middle. Pushed to long on for one.
Shorter ball, on off. Pushed to long on for one.
Beaten! Loopy ball, lands right on the off pole. De Silva looks to block but the ball turns sharply and goes past the outside edge.

Loopy ball, on off. Blocked out.

OUT! LBW! Umpire's call on hitting! Flatter ball, on middle and leg. Lakmal goes back to block but gets hit on the pads. The finger goes up but Lakmal decides this one. There is no bat on it and Ball Tracker shows umpire's call on hitting!

Full ball, on middle and leg. De Silva gets the inside edge past square leg while looking to block. Single taken.

Full ball, on the pads. Blocked out.

SIX! High and handsome! Tossed up, on middle and leg. Lakmal comes down the track and heaves it over the long on fence.
Full ball, on middle. Lakmal blocks it out.
Flatter ball, around off. Pushed past covers for one.
Flatter ball, on off. Lakmal blocks this and survives.
Shorter ball, lands outside off and turns away. Lakmal thinks of cutting it but then leaves it alone.
Full ball, on off. Lakmal plays it back to the bowler.
Full ball, on off. Pushed to long off for one.
Down the leg side and Dhananjaya de Silva kicks it away.
Tossed up, on the pads. Blocked out.

On the pads and nudged down towards short fine leg for another run.

Slightly shorter, on off. Dhananjaya de Silva punches it off the back foot through cover and gets yet another brace.
Tossed up, on off and gently pushed back towards the bowler.

Nicely flighted, around middle and leg. Ramesh Mendis strides out and works it towards mid-wicket.
On middle and defended out by Mendis.

Huge appeal but not given. Tossed up, around the leg stump. Dhananjaya de Silva looks for the reverse sweep yet again but misses and gets hit on the pads. The umpire shakes his head, probably pitching outside leg.

Tossed up, around leg stump. Dhananjaya de Silva plays the reverse sweep behind point and picks up a couple of runs. A short run is signaled though as Dhananjaya de Silva was a bit too eager to get back to the other end.
Flatter one, around off. Dhananjaya de Silva defends it out on the off side.

Tossed up, on the pads. Dhananjaya de Silva blocks it off the front foot.

A single as this is pushed down to long off.

Dinesh Chandimal looks baffled and Chase is elated. Can the visitors build on this and get rid of the tailenders?

Back of a length, around leg stump and worked past short mid-wicket for a run.
Good-length ball, on off and angling in. Dinesh Chandimal gets right behind the line of the ball to block it.
Very full, on off and Dinesh Chandimal digs it out towards short cover.
Fullish ball, around off and pushed back towards the bowler.
On off and defended off the front foot by Dhananjaya de Silva.
On middle, nudged out towards cover-point for a quick single. Dinesh Chandimal is off the mark with that as well.
Nicely bowled. Floated up, around middle and leg. Chandimal is able to block it out.
Short ball, around off stump. Dhananjaya de Silva rocks back and pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
Down the leg side and spinning further away, Dhananjaya de Silva shoulders arms.
Angled across from around the wicket, on off stump. Dhananjaya de Silva defends it off the back foot.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is going to be Roston Chase. His figures read 16-2-43-1 so far.
Good-length ball, around middle and kept out on the leg side by Chandimal.
Length again, over off stump. Chandimal stays solid in defense.
An in-dipper this time from Holder, on middle and leg. Dinesh Chandimal pushes it back to the bowler who throws the ball back towards the batter.
A length ball, outside off and stroked away towards cover-point.
Back of a length, around off and angled in. Dhananjaya de Silva dabs it down towards backward square leg where the fielder makes a good stop. They take a single.
A gentle fullish ball, on off. Dhananjaya de Silva pushes it to mid on.

The second session is set to begin. The West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Dhananjaya de Silva and Dinesh Chandimal, the new batsman, who walk out to bat for Sri Lanka. Jason Holder to start with the ball. So, we start off with some pace attack here.
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

Right then. Sri Lanka will hope to come back and bat for as long as they could and swell the lead. We have a lot of time on our hands, even after a few sessions lost due to rain in this second Test. West Indies will be looking to pick wickets at regular intervals to put the hosts in a spot of bother. Another exciting session awaits. Do join us for the second session at 12:40 pm local (7:10 am GMT).

West Indies could not put a lid on the run flow. It was Permaul who got the only wicket of the session early on, as he got rid of Asalanka. But after that, the bowlers probed good lines and lengths but were unable to cause any trouble to the batters. The West Indies skipper, Brathwaite, tried out various combinations, earlier with the spinners and later he introduced a pacer for the first time in this innings for the 47th over. But there was no change to the trajectory until the last over of the session, when Chase put his hand up and broke the partnership which was worrying the visitors.

Nissanka kept his nerves calm and made sure to take his side to safer shores. The overnight batters came back and fared really well. But Asalanka gave a dolly to short leg and was dismissed. Since then, the pair of de Silva and Nissanka stitched a crucial partnership to swell their lead. But Nissanka well right before Lunch and Sri Lanka go back with a lead of 102 runs.

It was a good session of cricket. Both the teams gave it their all. A wicket for the West Indies at the stroke of Lunch changes the trajectory of the game. The hosts lost a wicket early on and later a wicket to ruin their Lunch break, as they lost Nissanka right at the end. West Indies will have the momentum on their side.
Review! Pathum Nissanka has reviewed this LBW decision.

On a length, around off. Dhananjaya de Silva goes on the back foot and taps it past short leg for a single.

Tossed up, on middle and driven to wide of mid on for a quick single.

Length ball, on the pads. Nissanka works it to deep square leg for one.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Holder starts off with a length ball, down the leg side. Pathum Nissanka looks to flick it away but the ball brushes the pads as Joshua Da Silva dives down to his left to pouch it.

On middle, Dhananjaya de Silva manages to keep it out.
On a length, outside off. Pathum Nissanka dabs it down towards short third man and picks up a run. He moves to 49 now.

We are ready for play! The umpires are out in the middle and so are the West Indies players. Out come the overnight batters for Sri Lanka, Charith Asalanka and Pathum Nissanka. Roston Chase to start proceedings with the ball on Day 4.

PITCH REPORT - Farveez Maharoof says that the pitch is rough and the spinners will get plenty of assistance. Aamir Sohail joins him and says that the batters should make adjustments to their shoulder alignment.

Even though West Indies could not make the most of their advantage. Their batters fought till the end to get a decent lead on them. When they came back to the field, the pack was very lively which caused some trouble for the opposition. West Indies scalped two wickets through run-outs and would come back on the field with the same intent. If West Indies are able to pick a couple of wickets in the opening session, will put them in a comfortable position. Another great day of Test cricket awaits.

The Sri Lankan spinners did their magic and helped their side stage a comeback in the game. Ramesh Mendis was the star with the ball, as he bagged a six-wicket haul. He was supported well by Lasith and Praveen from the other end who picked two scalps each to make sure the visitors don’t swell their lead over 49 runs. Although, their batters started off shakily, with a couple of run outs that would hurt them quite a bit. They lost their skipper, Karunaratne and soon after Fernando slipped out as well. The hosts now need their batters to calm their nerves and bat for as long as they could. A lead of 150 runs will be enough to trouble the visitors, as this pitch gets trickier as the game moves by.

Hello and welcome to Day 4 of this second Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies. Day 3 did what it is known for, it was a moving day, and the advantage moved back and forth. Let us hope we have another riveting day of Test cricket in store for us with no rain interruptions.

That is it from Day 3 of the second Test between Sri Lanka and West Indies. The rain gods have stayed away and we were able to witness another intriguing day of Test cricket. We look forward to your company on Day 4 of this Test which promises to be an exciting one and it will commence at 9.45 am local (4.15 am GMT). Cheers!

Sri Lanka were in a dominating position at the halfway mark on Day 3 but they leaked a few runs at the fag end of Windies' innings and conceded a lead of 49 runs. Their spinners were brilliant to bring them back into this Test, as at one point, it looked like West Indies were on course to get a huge first innings lead. However, when they came out to bat they looked a bit out of sorts as Dimuth Karunaratne ran himself out. Oshada Fernando and Pathum Nissanka tried to steady the ship but a miscommunication in the middle saw Fernando walking back to the hut. Charith Asalanka joined Nissanka and they both made sure that there was no further damage. These two overnight batters will look to bat long on Day 4 and take their team to safer shores.

West Indies would be happier of the two sides at the end of the day's play and would feel that they have their noses slightly ahead. However, they have to bat last on this wicket and a target of anywhere around 150 isn't going to be easy for West Indies. They were not able to capitalize on the start that they got and lost wickets in clusters in the second session. Kyle Mayers played a handy innings at the end and the visitors managed to get a lead of 49 runs. The Windies came out with intent as they were top-notch in the field. The spinners kept things tight and it resulted in a couple of run outs which put them in the driver's seat. They would look to strike early on Day 4 and make sure that the Lankans do not run away with the lead.

Dimuth Karunaratne, the skipper of Sri Lanka, says that before the series started, he was a bit worried but the team has done really well. Pathum Nissanka for the way he opened in this series and says that he has a bright future. Says that Oshada Fernando may not have the best of series with the bat but played an important role in the field. Credits Mickey Arthur and says that he was always supportive of the team when they struggled and wishes Arthur the best for his future. He ends by thanking the fans in the local language.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the skipper of West Indies, is up for a chat. He says that the batting in the first innings was very crucial for the side. He adds that he missed out on his century and maybe that could have been the difference in hindsight. He says that they got starts but were unable to capitalize on it. Mentions that the positives are the potential of the players. They have players to turn the game around, but he thinks as a batting unit, they will look to be more hungry and make sure to learn from this series.

Ramesh Mendis is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES! He says that he is pleased to bowl this well for his country and he is thankful for the support he got from the captain and the entire team. Adds that he thanks his coaches and says that he worked really hard in the last few years. Informs that he is more of a bowling all-rounder now but he wants to bat well for the team too.

Dhananjaya de Silva is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH! He says that he always believes in himself under pressure and he is glad he could perform for his side. Mentions that it was very tough as the ball was turning. Adds that they had to bat long and that was the plan. He ends by wishing good luck to Mickey Arthur and Grant Flower and thanking both of them.
Stay tuned for the presenatation.

Sri Lanka got off to a sloppy start, as they lost a couple of early wickets, both via run out towards the end of Day 3. They started off well on Day 4 though and were able to cut the deficit and were marching on their way to swell the lead. It was not easy and they found themselves in big trouble when there at 221-8. If not for Dhananjaya de Silva, the hosts could’ve been in a lot of trouble. But he anchored the innings really well with his 155*. He was supported well for the ninth-wicket stand by Lasith Embuldeniya. They both managed to tire out the bowlers and extended the lead to 296 runs. Such a big target was always going to be difficult for West Indies to chase down but they didn't even manage to play out for a draw and were bowled out within two sessions.

West Indies started quite well with the bat. Kraigg Brathwaite was at the heart of two important stands. He racked up a 62-run stand with Jermaine Blackwood and later stitched a partnership of 75 runs for the second wicket along with Nkrumah Bonner, but once this stand was broken, the wickets kept falling for the visitors. They could not negotiate the spin well. But a late stand between Kyle Mayers and Veerasammy Permaul made sure West Indies take back a decent lead with them of 49 runs before getting bowled out. Spin continued to dominate the game as Ramesh Mendis took 6 wickets. But the Windies had a handy lead.

In the first innings, after two sessions were lost due to rain on Day 1, Sri Lanka started off well. The opening stand of Dimuth Karunaratane and Pathum Nissanka flourished yet again in this series. The skipper got out after getting a start but Nissanka carried on and scored a fine fifty. The departure of the top order though resulted in a capitulation of the Sri Lankan middle order as they were bowled out for 204. Veerasammy Permaul was the start of the ball for West Indies as he took a 5-wicket while Jomel Warrican took 4 wickets.

But an over of Ramesh Mendis changed everything. The off-spinner took 3 wickets in a single over and rocked the middle order of West Indies. Only formalities were left after that as Ramesh Mendis and Lasith Embuldeniya each took their 5-wicket haul to finish the game right before the scheduled Tea break.

Sri Lanka did not bat much in the first session and declared after facing only a handful of overs. A target of 297 was a big one and it was clear that West Indies were looking to draw it. Kraigg Brathwaite fell quite early but Jermaine Blackwood and Nkrumah Bonner stitched a solid stand. The wicket of Blackwood just before Lunch was a big one for Sri Lanka. But Shai Hope joined Bonner and both of them were looking very solid in the middle. It looked like these two batters will bat till Tea at the very least.

Wow, what a show by Sri Lanka! The two spinners, Ramesh Mendis and Lasith Embuldeniya took 5 wickets each to demolish the batting order of West Indies. It is only apt that both of them lead their team out of the field. All smiles in the Sri Lankan camp!

Right then. Both the teams have their task cut out. Will Sri Lanka get the 8 scalps or will West Indies survive the brutal spin attack? We will have a better idea of how this game will pan out, after the Lunch break. Do join us for the live action at 1240 local (0710 GMT).

The spinners are on top! Sri Lanka came out to bat at the beginning of Day 5. They faced three overs and declared just after Lasith Embuldeniya got bowled off Holder. Without any second thought, it was all spin for the hosts. Lasith and Mendis started from each end, but this time they were unable to cause any real threat. Mendis struck early on to get rid of the opposition skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite. But since then, they probed good lines and lengths but the batsmen were on top of it. But luckily for the hosts, Embuldeniya worked his magic and struck in the final over before Lunch to change the trajectory of the game.

West Indies began their day with the ball, but Holder scalped a wicket in the third over of the day and the hosts declared after that. 297 is what the visitors have to chase down in three sessions. Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood came out with the bat, but the former slipped out early on. Then came a solid stand between Bonner and Blackwood, there was some miscommunication between the two, but they eluded the danger of getting run-out. But just as everything looked good for the visitors, Blackwood lost his track and gave away his wicket.

A breakthrough right at the stroke of Lunch changes everything. Sri Lankan camp will be confident going into the break and would look to tighten the nails in the next session. The visitors did really well, to recover from an early breakthrough, but to put salt on it, Blackwood got out just at the brink of Lunch.

Drinks! A pretty good start for West Indies despite losing Kraigg Brathwaite early. It looks like they are not going to go for the chase and just play for a draw. Sri Lanka need to be patient here and keep bowling in the right channels. A couple of quick wickets could be enough for them to have the game in their firm control.

A mix-up but safe! Tossed up, outside off. Bonner waits for it and guides it towards third man. The batters take a single. Bonner wanted the second run as well, he was halfway down the track. The fielder collects the ball and throws it towards the keeper rather than the non-striker's end, which allows Bonner to turn and gets back into his crease. He is not happy with Blackwood. Bonner says that it was his call, as he was running to the danger end.
Mendis gives it a little bit of air this time. Full and on off. Blackwood strides forward and looks to defend it out. The ball is aerial for a while but it falls besides the man at short leg.

There is no bat on that, Ball Tracker has umpire's call on impact and wickets are hitting!

Review! Kraigg Brathwaite takes the review for lbw. The on-field decision is out. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows it is upmire's call on impact and the ball is hitting the stumps and with that the skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite, has to walk back.
